lion residents making it the second largest conurbation in the world after Tokyo. The result is high urban density, which spells an enormous demand for the more efficient use of space and encourages verticalization in architecture. The publication outlines the current developments in South Korean architecture, urban development and landscape architecture by examining 32 projects in detail. An in-depth view of contemporary South Korean architecture is given by five essays that address topics such as the fusion of tradition and the modern, the re-defining of so-called "social spaces" and the country's special topographical situation.The authors are both architects, trained at the Harvard Graduate School of Design.  aKoreanische Architektur heute: eine Synthese aus kultureller Identität und und westlicher Entwurfshaltung  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitectszKorea (South). 0aArchitecturezKorea (South)xHistory. 0aCity planningzKorea (South)y21st century. 4aKorea. 4aKorean Architecture. 4aUrbanism. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh1 aHong, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHong, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHong-Bin, Kang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyungmin, Pai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJin, Baek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJungyoon, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Jinhee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSong, Kimm Joung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWon-Joon, Choi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoonjin, Park, econtribut